          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How do you calculate depreciation on fixed assets?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Straight line depreciation equals cost minus residual value divided by useful life, and the written down value method applies a fixed percentage to the opening carrying amount each year. Schedule II of the Companies Act 2013 sets the useful lives and caps residual value at 5 percent of cost. A Rs 10,00,000 machine with a 15 year life gives about Rs 63,333 a year."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What are fixed assets and current assets?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Fixed assets are held for long-term use in the business and are not meant for resale, such as land, buildings, plant and vehicles, while current assets are expected to convert into cash within twelve months, such as stock, debtors and bank balances. A delivery van in a logistics firm is a fixed asset; the same van in a dealership showroom is stock in trade."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Loss on sale of fixed assets is disallowed under which section?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Loss on sale of a fixed asset is added back while computing business income under Section 37 read with Section 32, because it is capital in nature and not an expenditure laid out for business. Depreciable assets are instead handled through the block of assets under Section 43(6), and any shortfall or surplus on sale is taxed as short-term capital gain under Section 50."
          }
        }
